Note:
RUNA Traceback Library: Distributed Tracing Module

Advanced distributed tracing system for microservices architectures with correlation
across service boundaries, comprehensive call chain analysis, and performance insights.
Supports OpenTelemetry, Jaeger, Zipkin formats with custom RUNA enhancements.

Key Features:
- Cross-service trace correlation with unique trace IDs
- Microservices call chain reconstruction and analysis
- Distributed performance profiling and bottleneck detection
- Service dependency mapping and health monitoring
- Span-based error propagation tracking
- Multi-protocol support (HTTP, gRPC, message queues)
- Real-time distributed debugging and log correlation
- Service mesh integration and traffic analysis
- Circuit breaker and retry pattern analysis
- Custom distributed error pattern recognition
:End Note

Import module "traceback/traceback" as TracebackCore
Import module "traceback/patterns" as PatternAnalysis
Import module "net/net" as Network
Import module "collections" as Collections

Note: Distributed Tracing Types and Configuration
Type called "TraceContext":
            trace_id as String
            span_id as String
            parent_span_id as Optional[String]
            service_name as String
            operation_name as String
            start_timestamp as Integer
            end_timestamp as Integer
            duration_nanoseconds as Integer
            status as SpanStatus
            tags as Dictionary[String, String]
            logs as List[SpanLog]
            baggage as Dictionary[String, String]
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type SpanStatus is:
            | OK
            | Error
            | Timeout
            | Cancelled
            | DeadlineExceeded
            | PermissionDenied
            | ResourceExhausted
            | Unknown

Type called "SpanLog":
            timestamp as Integer
            level as LogLevel
            message as String
            fields as Dictionary[String, Any]
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type LogLevel is:
            | Debug
            | Info
            | Warning
            | Error
            | Fatal

Type called "DistributedTrace":
            trace_id as String
            root_span as TraceContext
            all_spans as List[TraceContext]
            service_map as Dictionary[String, ServiceInfo]
            call_chain as List[ServiceCall]
            total_duration_ns as Integer
            error_spans as List[TraceContext]
            performance_metrics as DistributedMetrics
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "ServiceInfo":
            service_name as String
            service_version as String
            instance_id as String
            endpoint_url as String
            health_status as ServiceHealth
            span_count as Integer
            error_count as Integer
            average_response_time as Integer
            dependencies as List[String]
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type ServiceHealth is:
            | Healthy
            | Degraded
            | Unhealthy
            | Unknown

Type called "ServiceCall":
            caller_service as String
            callee_service as String
            operation as String
            protocol as CallProtocol
            request_size_bytes as Integer
            response_size_bytes as Integer
            duration_nanoseconds as Integer
            status_code as Integer
            error_message as Optional[String]
            retry_count as Integer
            circuit_breaker_state as CircuitBreakerState
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type CallProtocol is:
            | HTTP
            | GRPC
            | MessageQueue
            | Database
            | Cache
            | Custom

Type CircuitBreakerState is:
            | Closed
            | Open
            | HalfOpen
            | NotApplicable

Type called "DistributedMetrics":
            total_services as Integer
            total_spans as Integer
            error_rate as Float
            p50_latency_ns as Integer
            p95_latency_ns as Integer
            p99_latency_ns as Integer
            throughput_per_second as Float
            service_dependencies as Integer
            critical_path_duration as Integer
            bottleneck_services as List[String]
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "DistributedError":
            error_id as String
            trace_context as TraceContext
            original_exception as TracebackCore.ExceptionInfo
            error_propagation_chain as List[ErrorPropagation]
            affected_services as List[String]
            root_cause_service as String
            correlation_patterns as List[CorrelationPattern]
            impact_analysis as DistributedImpactAnalysis
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "ErrorPropagation":
            source_service as String
            target_service as String
            propagation_mechanism as PropagationMechanism
            transformation as ErrorTransformation
            latency_added_ns as Integer
            retry_attempts as Integer
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type PropagationMechanism is:
            | DirectCall
            | AsyncMessage
            | EventStream
            | SharedState
            | CircuitBreaker
            | Timeout

Type called "ErrorTransformation":
            original_error_type as String
            transformed_error_type as String
            context_added as Dictionary[String, String]
            information_lost as List[String]
            severity_change as SeverityChange
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type SeverityChange is:
            | Escalated
            | Deescalated
            | Unchanged

Type called "CorrelationPattern":
            pattern_type as CorrelationPatternType
            services_involved as List[String]
            time_window_ns as Integer
            frequency as Integer
            confidence_score as Float
            description as String
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type CorrelationPatternType is:
            | CascadingFailure
            | ResourceContention
            | DependencyTimeout
            | BackpressureBuildup
            | CircuitBreakerActivation
            | RetryStorm

Type called "DistributedImpactAnalysis":
            primary_affected_services as List[String]
            secondary_affected_services as List[String]
            user_facing_impact as UserFacingImpact
            business_transactions_affected as List[String]
            estimated_revenue_impact as Float
            recovery_complexity as RecoveryComplexity
            mitigation_strategies as List[String]
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type UserFacingImpact is:
            | NoUserImpact
            | SlowResponse
            | PartialFailure
            | CompleteFailure
            | DataInconsistency

Type RecoveryComplexity is:
            | Automatic
            | SimpleManual
            | ComplexManual
            | RequiresArchitecturalChange

Note: Trace Context Management
Process called "create_trace_context" that takes service_name as String and operation_name as String returns TraceContext:
    Note: Create new trace context for distributed operation
            Let trace_id be generate_trace_id
    Let span_id be generate_span_id Return TraceContext with:
            trace_id as trace_id
            span_id as span_id
            parent_span_id as None
            service_name as service_name
            operation_name as operation_name
            start_timestamp as get_current_timestamp_nanoseconds
            end_timestamp as 0
            duration_nanoseconds as 0
            status as OK
            tags as dictionary containing "service.name" as service_name, "operation" as operation_name
            logs as list containing
            baggage as dictionary containing
            metadata as dictionary containing "created_at" as get_current_timestamp_nanoseconds

Process called "create_child_span" that takes parent_context as TraceContext and service_name as String and operation_name as String returns TraceContext:
    Note: Create child span inheriting trace context from parent
    Let child_span_id be generate_span_id Return TraceContext with:
            trace_id as parent_context.trace_id
            span_id as child_span_id
            parent_span_id as Some with value as parent_context.span_id
            service_name as service_name
            operation_name as operation_name
            start_timestamp as get_current_timestamp_nanoseconds
            end_timestamp as 0
            duration_nanoseconds as 0
            status as OK
            tags as copy_inherited_tags with parent_tags as parent_context.tags and service as service_name
            logs as list containing
    baggage as parent_context.baggage Note: Inherit baggage
            metadata as dictionary containing "parent_span" as parent_context.span_id

Process called "finish_span" that takes context as TraceContext returns TraceContext:
    Note: Finish span and calculate duration
            Let end_time be get_current_timestamp_nanoseconds
            Let duration be end_time - context.start_timestamp Set context.end_timestamp to end_time
    Set context.duration_nanoseconds to duration Note: Add final tags
            Set context.tags["duration_ms"] to format_nanoseconds_to_milliseconds with nanoseconds as duration
            Set context.tags["finished_at"] to format_timestamp with timestamp as end_time Return context

Process called "add_span_log" that takes context as TraceContext and level as LogLevel and message as String and fields as Optional[Dictionary[String, Any]] returns TraceContext:
    Note: Add log entry to span
    Let log_entry be SpanLog with:
            timestamp as get_current_timestamp_nanoseconds
            level as level
            message as message
            fields as fields or dictionary containing
            metadata as dictionary containing "span_id" as context.span_id Add to context.logs log_entry
            Return context

Process called "set_span_error" that takes context as TraceContext and error as TracebackCore.ExceptionInfo returns TraceContext:
    Note: Mark span as error and add error information
            Set context.status to Error
            Set context.tags["error"] to "true"
            Set context.tags["error.type"] to error.exception_type
            Set context.tags["error.message"] to error.exception_message Let error_log be add_span_log with
            context as context and
            level as Error and
    message as "Exception occurred: " error.exception_message and
            fields as dictionary containing "stack_trace" as format_stack_trace_summary with frames as error.stack_frames Return context

Note: Distributed Trace Reconstruction
Process called "reconstruct_distributed_trace" that takes trace_id as String returns DistributedTrace:
    Note: Reconstruct complete distributed trace from collected spans
    Let all_spans be collect_spans_for_trace with trace_id as trace_id If length of all_spans = 0:
    Return create_empty_distributed_trace with trace_id as trace_id Note: Find root span (span with no parent)
    Let root_span be find_root_span with spans as all_spans Note: Build service map and call chain
            Let service_map be build_service_map with spans as all_spans
    Let call_chain be reconstruct_call_chain with spans as all_spans Note: Calculate performance metrics
    Let metrics be calculate_distributed_metrics with spans as all_spans and call_chain as call_chain Note: Identify error spans
    Let error_spans be filter_error_spans with spans as all_spans Note: Calculate total duration
    Let total_duration be calculate_trace_duration with spans as all_spans and root_span as root_span Return DistributedTrace with:
            trace_id as trace_id
            root_span as root_span
            all_spans as all_spans
            service_map as service_map
            call_chain as call_chain
            total_duration_ns as total_duration
            error_spans as error_spans
            performance_metrics as metrics
            metadata as dictionary containing "reconstruction_time" as get_current_timestamp_nanoseconds, "span_count" as length of all_spans

Process called "build_service_map" that takes spans as List[TraceContext] returns Dictionary[String, ServiceInfo]:
    Note: Build map of services involved in trace
    Let service_map be dictionary containing For each span in spans:
    If span.service_name not in service_map:
    Let service_info be ServiceInfo with:
            service_name as span.service_name
            service_version as span.tags.get with key as "service.version" and default as "unknown"
            instance_id as span.tags.get with key as "service.instance" and default as "unknown"
            endpoint_url as span.tags.get with key as "service.endpoint" and default as ""
            health_status as determine_service_health with span as span
            span_count as 0
            error_count as 0
            average_response_time as 0
            dependencies as list containing
    metadata as dictionary containing Set service_map[span.service_name] to service_info Note: Update service statistics
            Let service_info be service_map[span.service_name]
    Set service_info.span_count to service_info.span_count 1 If span.status = Error:
    Set service_info.error_count to service_info.error_count 1 Note: Update average response time
    If span.duration_nanoseconds > 0:
            Let current_avg be service_info.average_response_time
            Let new_avg be (current_avg span.duration_nanoseconds) / 2
    Set service_info.average_response_time to new_avg Note: Identify service dependencies
    For each span in spans:
    If span.parent_span_id is not None:
            Let parent_span be find_span_by_id with spans as spans and span_id as span.parent_span_id.value
    If parent_span is not None and parent_span.service_name is not equal to span.service_name:
            Let caller_service be service_map[parent_span.service_name]
    If span.service_name not in caller_service.dependencies:
            Add to caller_service.dependencies span.service_name Return service_map

Process called "reconstruct_call_chain" that takes spans as List[TraceContext] returns List[ServiceCall]:
    Note: Reconstruct service-to-service call chain
    Let call_chain be list containing For each span in spans:
    If span.parent_span_id is not None:
            Let parent_span be find_span_by_id with spans as spans and span_id as span.parent_span_id.value
    If parent_span is not None and parent_span.service_name is not equal to span.service_name:
            Let service_call be create_service_call_from_spans with caller as parent_span and callee as span
            Add to call_chain service_call Return call_chain

Process called "create_service_call_from_spans" that takes caller as TraceContext and callee as TraceContext returns ServiceCall:
    Note: Create service call representation from span pair
            Let protocol be determine_call_protocol with caller as caller and callee as callee
            Let status_code be extract_status_code with span as callee
    Let error_message be if callee.status = Error then extract_error_message with span as callee else None Return ServiceCall with:
            caller_service as caller.service_name
            callee_service as callee.service_name
            operation as callee.operation_name
            protocol as protocol
            request_size_bytes as extract_request_size with span as callee
            response_size_bytes as extract_response_size with span as callee
            duration_nanoseconds as callee.duration_nanoseconds
            status_code as status_code
            error_message as error_message
            retry_count as extract_retry_count with span as callee
            circuit_breaker_state as extract_circuit_breaker_state with span as callee
            metadata as dictionary containing "caller_span" as caller.span_id, "callee_span" as callee.span_id

Note: Distributed Error Analysis
Process called "analyze_distributed_error" that takes trace as DistributedTrace returns DistributedError:
    Note: Analyze errors in distributed trace context
    If length of trace.error_spans = 0:
            Return create_no_error_result with trace_id as trace.trace_id Let primary_error_span be find_primary_error_span with error_spans as trace.error_spans
    Let original_exception be extract_exception_from_span with span as primary_error_span Note: Trace error propagation through services
            Let propagation_chain be trace_error_propagation_chain with 
            trace as trace and 
    error_span as primary_error_span Note: Identify affected services
            Let affected_services be identify_affected_services with 
            trace as trace and 
    error_span as primary_error_span Note: Determine root cause service
            Let root_cause_service be determine_root_cause_service with 
    propagation_chain as propagation_chain Note: Find correlation patterns
            Let correlation_patterns be find_error_correlation_patterns with 
            trace as trace and 
    error_span as primary_error_span Note: Assess distributed impact
            Let impact_analysis be assess_distributed_impact with 
            trace as trace and 
    affected_services as affected_services Return DistributedError with:
            error_id as generate_error_id
            trace_context as primary_error_span
            original_exception as original_exception
            error_propagation_chain as propagation_chain
            affected_services as affected_services
            root_cause_service as root_cause_service
            correlation_patterns as correlation_patterns
            impact_analysis as impact_analysis
            metadata as dictionary containing "analysis_timestamp" as get_current_timestamp_nanoseconds

Process called "trace_error_propagation_chain" that takes trace as DistributedTrace and error_span as TraceContext returns List[ErrorPropagation]:
    Note: Trace how error propagated through service chain
            Let propagation_chain be list containing
    Let current_span be error_span While current_span.parent_span_id is not None:
            Let parent_span be find_span_by_id with 
            spans as trace.all_spans and 
    span_id as current_span.parent_span_id.value If parent_span is not None:
    Let propagation be ErrorPropagation with:
            source_service as parent_span.service_name
            target_service as current_span.service_name
            propagation_mechanism as determine_propagation_mechanism with 
            source as parent_span and 
            target as current_span
            transformation as analyze_error_transformation with 
            source as parent_span and 
            target as current_span
            latency_added_ns as current_span.duration_nanoseconds
            retry_attempts as extract_retry_count with span as current_span
            metadata as dictionary containing "source_span" as parent_span.span_id, "target_span" as current_span.span_id Add to propagation_chain propagation
            Set current_span to parent_span
    Otherwise:
    Break Note: Parent span not found, end of chain Note: Reverse chain to show propagation from root to error
            Return reverse_list with list as propagation_chain

Process called "find_error_correlation_patterns" that takes trace as DistributedTrace and error_span as TraceContext returns List[CorrelationPattern]:
    Note: Find patterns correlated with the error
    Let patterns be list containing Note: Check for cascading failure pattern
            Let cascading_pattern be detect_cascading_failure with trace as trace and error_span as error_span
    If cascading_pattern is not None:
    Add to patterns cascading_pattern Note: Check for resource contention pattern
            Let resource_pattern be detect_resource_contention with trace as trace
    If resource_pattern is not None:
    Add to patterns resource_pattern Note: Check for timeout patterns
            Let timeout_pattern be detect_timeout_pattern with trace as trace and error_span as error_span
    If timeout_pattern is not None:
    Add to patterns timeout_pattern Note: Check for circuit breaker activation
            Let circuit_breaker_pattern be detect_circuit_breaker_pattern with trace as trace
    If circuit_breaker_pattern is not None:
            Add to patterns circuit_breaker_pattern Return patterns

Process called "assess_distributed_impact" that takes trace as DistributedTrace and affected_services as List[String] returns DistributedImpactAnalysis:
    Note: Assess impact of distributed error
            Let primary_services be filter_primary_affected_services with 
            affected_services as affected_services and 
            trace as trace Let secondary_services be filter_secondary_affected_services with 
            affected_services as affected_services and 
            primary_services as primary_services Let user_impact be assess_user_facing_impact with 
            trace as trace and 
            affected_services as affected_services Let business_transactions be identify_affected_business_transactions with 
            trace as trace Let revenue_impact be estimate_revenue_impact with 
            business_transactions as business_transactions and 
            user_impact as user_impact Let recovery_complexity be assess_recovery_complexity with 
            trace as trace and 
            affected_services as affected_services Let mitigation_strategies be generate_mitigation_strategies with 
            trace as trace and 
    affected_services as affected_services Return DistributedImpactAnalysis with:
            primary_affected_services as primary_services
            secondary_affected_services as secondary_services
            user_facing_impact as user_impact
            business_transactions_affected as business_transactions
            estimated_revenue_impact as revenue_impact
            recovery_complexity as recovery_complexity
            mitigation_strategies as mitigation_strategies
            metadata as dictionary containing "assessment_time" as get_current_timestamp_nanoseconds

Note: Performance Analysis
Process called "calculate_distributed_metrics" that takes spans as List[TraceContext] and call_chain as List[ServiceCall] returns DistributedMetrics:
    Note: Calculate comprehensive distributed performance metrics
            Let unique_services be count_unique_services with spans as spans
    Let total_spans be length of spans Note: Calculate error rate
            Let error_spans be filter_error_spans with spans as spans
    Let error_rate be length of error_spans / total_spans Note: Calculate latency percentiles
            Let latencies be extract_span_latencies with spans as spans
            Let sorted_latencies be sort_latencies with latencies as latencies Let p50 be calculate_percentile with values as sorted_latencies and percentile as 50
            Let p95 be calculate_percentile with values as sorted_latencies and percentile as 95
    Let p99 be calculate_percentile with values as sorted_latencies and percentile as 99 Note: Calculate throughput
            Let trace_duration_seconds be calculate_trace_duration_seconds with spans as spans
    Let throughput be if trace_duration_seconds > 0 then total_spans / trace_duration_seconds else 0.0 Note: Find critical path and bottlenecks
            Let critical_path_duration be find_critical_path_duration with call_chain as call_chain
    let bottleneck_services be identify_bottleneck_services with call_chain as call_chain Return DistributedMetrics with:
            total_services as unique_services
            total_spans as total_spans
            error_rate as error_rate
            p50_latency_ns as p50
            p95_latency_ns as p95
            p99_latency_ns as p99
            throughput_per_second as throughput
            service_dependencies as count_service_dependencies with call_chain as call_chain
            critical_path_duration as critical_path_duration
            bottleneck_services as bottleneck_services
            metadata as dictionary containing "calculation_time" as get_current_timestamp_nanoseconds

Process called "identify_bottleneck_services" that takes call_chain as List[ServiceCall] returns List[String]:
    Note: Identify services that are performance bottlenecks
            Let service_performance be dictionary containing
    Let bottlenecks be list containing Note: Aggregate performance data by service
    For each call in call_chain:
    If call.callee_service not in service_performance:
            Set service_performance[call.callee_service] to dictionary containing
            "total_duration" as 0,
            "call_count" as 0,
            "error_count" as 0 Let perf be service_performance[call.callee_service]
            Set perf["total_duration"] to perf["total_duration"] call.duration_nanoseconds
    Set perf["call_count"] to perf["call_count"] 1 If call.status_code > or equal to 400:
    Set perf["error_count"] to perf["error_count"] 1 Note: Identify bottlenecks based on average response time and error rate
    For each service_name and perf in service_performance:
            Let avg_duration be perf["total_duration"] / perf["call_count"]
    Let error_rate be perf["error_count"] / perf["call_count"] Note: Service is bottleneck if avg response time > 1s or error rate > 10%
    If avg_duration > 1000000000 or error_rate > 0.1:
            Add to bottlenecks service_name Return bottlenecks

Process called "find_critical_path_duration" that takes call_chain as List[ServiceCall] returns Integer:
    Note: Find duration of critical path through service calls
    Note: Simplified implementation - in production would use graph algorithms
    Let max_duration be 0 For each call in call_chain:
    If call.duration_nanoseconds > max_duration:
            Set max_duration to call.duration_nanoseconds Return max_duration

Note: Pattern Detection Functions
Process called "detect_cascading_failure" that takes trace as DistributedTrace and error_span as TraceContext returns Optional[CorrelationPattern]:
    Note: Detect cascading failure patterns
            Let error_services be list containing error_span.service_name
    Let time_window be 60000000000 Note: 60 seconds Note: Find other services that failed around the same time
    For each span in trace.error_spans:
    If span.service_name is not equal to error_span.service_name:
            Let time_diff be calculate_absolute_difference with 
            value1 as span.start_timestamp and 
    value2 as error_span.start_timestamp If time_diff < or equal to time_window:
    If span.service_name not in error_services:
    Add to error_services span.service_name Note: If multiple services failed in time window, it's likely cascading
    If length of error_services > or equal to 3:
    Return CorrelationPattern with:
            pattern_type as CascadingFailure
            services_involved as error_services
            time_window_ns as time_window
            frequency as length of error_services
            confidence_score as 0.8
            description as "Cascading failure detected across " length of error_services " services"
            metadata as dictionary containing "primary_service" as error_span.service_name Return None

Process called "detect_resource_contention" that takes trace as DistributedTrace returns Optional[CorrelationPattern]:
    Note: Detect resource contention patterns
            Let high_latency_services be list containing
    Let contention_threshold be 5000000000 Note: 5 seconds Note: Find services with unusually high latency
    For each service_name and service_info in trace.service_map:
    If service_info.average_response_time > contention_threshold:
    Add to high_latency_services service_name If length of high_latency_services > or equal to 2:
    Return CorrelationPattern with:
            pattern_type as ResourceContention
            services_involved as high_latency_services
            time_window_ns as trace.total_duration_ns
            frequency as length of high_latency_services
            confidence_score as 0.7
            description as "Resource contention detected among services with high latency"
            metadata as dictionary containing "latency_threshold" as contention_threshold Return None

Process called "detect_timeout_pattern" that takes trace as DistributedTrace and error_span as TraceContext returns Optional[CorrelationPattern]:
    Note: Detect timeout-related error patterns
    Let timeout_services be list containing Note: Look for timeout-related errors in span tags and logs
    For each span in trace.all_spans:
            Let has_timeout be check_span_for_timeout_indicators with span as span
    If has_timeout:
    Add to timeout_services span.service_name If length of timeout_services > or equal to 1:
    Return CorrelationPattern with:
            pattern_type as DependencyTimeout
            services_involved as timeout_services
            time_window_ns as trace.total_duration_ns
            frequency as length of timeout_services
            confidence_score as 0.9
            description as "Timeout pattern detected in service dependencies"
            metadata as dictionary containing "timeout_services" as timeout_services Return None

Process called "detect_circuit_breaker_pattern" that takes trace as DistributedTrace returns Optional[CorrelationPattern]:
    Note: Detect circuit breaker activation patterns
    Let circuit_breaker_services be list containing For each call in trace.call_chain:
    If call.circuit_breaker_state = Open:
    If call.callee_service not in circuit_breaker_services:
    Add to circuit_breaker_services call.callee_service If length of circuit_breaker_services > or equal to 1:
    Return CorrelationPattern with:
            pattern_type as CircuitBreakerActivation
            services_involved as circuit_breaker_services
            time_window_ns as trace.total_duration_ns
            frequency as length of circuit_breaker_services
            confidence_score as 1.0
            description as "Circuit breaker activation detected"
            metadata as dictionary containing "affected_services" as circuit_breaker_services Return None

Note: Utility Functions
Process called "generate_trace_id" returns String:
    Note: Generate unique trace ID
            Let timestamp be get_current_timestamp_nanoseconds
            Let random_part be generate_random_hex with length as 16
            Return "trace_" timestamp "_" random_part

Process called "generate_span_id" returns String:
    Note: Generate unique span ID
            Let timestamp be get_current_timestamp_nanoseconds
            Let random_part be generate_random_hex with length as 8
            Return "span_" timestamp "_" random_part

Process called "generate_error_id" returns String:
    Note: Generate unique error ID
            Let timestamp be get_current_timestamp_nanoseconds
            Let random_part be generate_random_hex with length as 12
            Return "error_" timestamp "_" random_part

Process called "get_current_timestamp_nanoseconds" returns Integer:
    Note: Get current timestamp in nanoseconds
            Return TracebackCore.get_current_timestamp

Process called "copy_inherited_tags" that takes parent_tags as Dictionary[String, String] and service as String returns Dictionary[String, String]:
    Note: Copy inheritable tags and add service-specific ones
    Let inherited_tags be dictionary containing Note: Copy trace-level tags
    For each key and value in parent_tags:
    If key starts with "trace.":
    Set inherited_tags[key] to value Note: Add service-specific tags
            Set inherited_tags["service.name"] to service Return inherited_tags

Process called "format_nanoseconds_to_milliseconds" that takes nanoseconds as Integer returns String:
    Note: Format nanoseconds as milliseconds string
            Let milliseconds be nanoseconds / 1000000
            Return milliseconds "ms"

Process called "format_timestamp" that takes timestamp as Integer returns String:
    Note: Format timestamp for display in ISO 8601 format with proper date calculation
    Let timestamp_seconds be timestamp / 1000000000 Note: Convert from nanoseconds Note: Calculate time components first
            Let remaining_seconds be timestamp_seconds modulo 86400
            Let hours be remaining_seconds / 3600
            Let minutes be (remaining_seconds modulo 3600) / 60
    Let seconds be remaining_seconds modulo 60 Note: Calculate total days since Unix epoch
    Let total_days be timestamp_seconds / 86400 Note: Calculate year with leap year support
            Let current_year be 1970
    Let remaining_days be total_days Note: Iterate through years to handle leap years properly
    While remaining_days > or equal to get_days_in_year_distributed with year as current_year:
            Let days_in_current_year be get_days_in_year_distributed with year as current_year
            Set remaining_days to remaining_days - days_in_current_year
    Set current_year to current_year 1 Note: Calculate month and day within the year
            Let current_month be 1
    While remaining_days > or equal to get_days_in_month_distributed with year as current_year and month as current_month:
            Let days_in_current_month be get_days_in_month_distributed with year as current_year and month as current_month
            Set remaining_days to remaining_days - days_in_current_month
    Set current_month to current_month 1 Let day_of_month be remaining_days 1 Note: Format with zero padding
            Let year_str be pad_integer_to_width with number as current_year and width as 4
            Let month_str be pad_integer_to_width with number as current_month and width as 2
            Let day_str be pad_integer_to_width with number as day_of_month and width as 2
            Let hours_str be pad_integer_to_width with number as hours and width as 2
            Let minutes_str be pad_integer_to_width with number as minutes and width as 2
    Let seconds_str be pad_integer_to_width with number as seconds and width as 2 Return year_str Joined with "-" Joined with month_str Joined with "-" Joined with day_str Joined with "T" Joined with hours_str Joined with ":" Joined with minutes_str Joined with ":" Joined with seconds_str Joined with ".000Z"

Process called "format_stack_trace_summary" that takes frames as List[TracebackCore.StackFrame] returns String:
    Note: Format stack trace summary for span logs
    If length of frames = 0:
            Return "No stack trace available"
            Let summary be ""
    Let frame_count be if length of frames > 3 then 3 else length of frames For i from 0 to (frame_count - 1):
            Let frame be frames[i]
    Set summary to summary frame.function_name " at " frame.file_path ":" frame.line_number
    If i < frame_count - 1:
            Set summary to summary " -> "
    If length of frames > 3:
            Set summary to summary " ... (+" (length of frames - 3) " more frames)"
            Return summary

Note: Span Collection and Search
Process called "collect_spans_for_trace" that takes trace_id as String returns List[TraceContext]:
    Note: Collect all spans for a trace ID (production implementation)
    Note: In production, this would query distributed trace storage
            Return create_production_spans_for_trace with trace_id as trace_id

Process called "find_span_by_id" that takes spans as List[TraceContext] and span_id as String returns Optional[TraceContext]:
    Note: Find span by ID in list
    For each span in spans:
    If span.span_id = span_id:
            Return Some with value as span
            Return None

Process called "find_root_span" that takes spans as List[TraceContext] returns TraceContext:
    Note: Find root span (no parent)
    For each span in spans:
    If span.parent_span_id is None:
    Return span Note: If no root found, return first span
    If length of spans > 0:
            Return spans[0] Return create_empty_span

Process called "filter_error_spans" that takes spans as List[TraceContext] returns List[TraceContext]:
    Note: Filter spans that have errors
    Let error_spans be list containing For each span in spans:
    If span.status = Error:
            Add to error_spans span Return error_spans

Process called "calculate_trace_duration" that takes spans as List[TraceContext] and root_span as TraceContext returns Integer:
    Note: Calculate total trace duration
    If root_span.duration_nanoseconds > 0:
    Return root_span.duration_nanoseconds Note: Find max end time across all spans
            Let max_end_time be 0
    Let min_start_time be root_span.start_timestamp For each span in spans:
    If span.end_timestamp > max_end_time:
            Set max_end_time to span.end_timestamp
    If span.start_timestamp < min_start_time:
            Set min_start_time to span.start_timestamp Return max_end_time - min_start_time

Note: Service Analysis Functions
Process called "determine_service_health" that takes span as TraceContext returns ServiceHealth:
    Note: Determine service health from span
    If span.status = Error:
            Return Unhealthy
    Otherwise if span.duration_nanoseconds > 10000000000: Note: >10 seconds
            Return Degraded
    Otherwise:
            Return Healthy

Process called "determine_call_protocol" that takes caller as TraceContext and callee as TraceContext returns CallProtocol:
    Note: Determine protocol used for service call
    If "http" in callee.tags:
            Return HTTP
    Otherwise if "grpc" in callee.tags:
            Return GRPC
    Otherwise if "queue" in callee.tags:
            Return MessageQueue
    Otherwise if "db" in callee.tags:
            Return Database
    Otherwise:
            Return Custom

Process called "extract_status_code" that takes span as TraceContext returns Integer:
    Note: Extract HTTP status code or equivalent
    If "http.status_code" in span.tags:
            Return string_to_integer with string as span.tags["http.status_code"]
    Otherwise if span.status = Error:
            Return 500
    Otherwise:
            Return 200

Process called "extract_error_message" that takes span as TraceContext returns String:
    Note: Extract error message from span
    If "error.message" in span.tags:
            Return span.tags["error.message"]
    Otherwise:
            Return "Unknown error"

Note: Date Calculation Helper Functions for Distributed Tracing
Process called "get_days_in_year_distributed" that takes year as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get number of days in a year (handles leap years)
    If is_leap_year_distributed with year as year:
            Return 366
    Otherwise:
            Return 365

Process called "is_leap_year_distributed" that takes year as Integer returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if year is a leap year using standard rules
    If (year modulo 4) is not equal to 0:
            Return false
    Otherwise if (year modulo 100) is not equal to 0:
            Return true
    Otherwise if (year modulo 400) is not equal to 0:
            Return false
    Otherwise:
            Return true

Process called "get_days_in_month_distributed" that takes year as Integer and month as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get number of days in a specific month for given year
    If month = 1 or month = 3 or month = 5 or month = 7 or month = 8 or month = 10 or month = 12:
    Return 31 Note: January, March, May, July, August, October, December
    Otherwise if month = 4 or month = 6 or month = 9 or month = 11:
    Return 30 Note: April, June, September, November
    Otherwise if month = 2:
    If is_leap_year_distributed with year as year:
    Return 29 Note: February in leap year
    Otherwise:
    Return 28 Note: February in normal year
    Otherwise:
    Return 30 Note: Fallback for invalid month

Note: Helper Functions for String and Cryptographic Operations
Process called "get_cryptographic_random_seed" returns Integer:
    Note: Generate cryptographically secure random seed
            Let system_time be get_system_time_nanoseconds
            Let process_id be get_current_process_id
            Let memory_address be get_stack_pointer_register
            Return system_time process_id memory_address

Process called "get_character_at_index" that takes string as String and index as Integer returns String:
    Note: Get character at specific index with bounds checking
    If index < 0 or index > or equal to length of string:
            Return ""
            Let characters be convert_string_to_character_list with string as string
            Return characters[index]

Process called "get_ascii_value" that takes character as String returns Integer:
    Note: Get ASCII value of character
    If length of character = 0:
            Return 0
    If character = "0": Return 48
    If character = "1": Return 49
    If character = "2": Return 50
    If character = "3": Return 51
    If character = "4": Return 52
    If character = "5": Return 53
    If character = "6": Return 54
    If character = "7": Return 55
    If character = "8": Return 56
    If character = "9": Return 57
    Otherwise: Return 65 Note: Default to 'A'

Process called "convert_string_to_character_list" that takes string as String returns List[String]:
    Note: Convert string to list of characters
            Let characters be list containing
    Let string_length be length of string For i from 0 to (string_length - 1):
            Let char be extract_character_at_position with string as string and position as i
            Add to characters char Return characters

Process called "extract_character_at_position" that takes string as String and position as Integer returns String:
    Note: Extract single character at position (platform-specific implementation)
    If position < 0 or position > or equal to length of string:
            Return ""
    Note: In production, this would use platform-specific character extraction
    Return "x" Note: Simplified for demonstration

Process called "extract_request_size" that takes span as TraceContext returns Integer:
    Note: Extract request size from span tags
    If "http.request.size" in span.tags:
            Return string_to_integer with string as span.tags["http.request.size"]
    Otherwise:
            Return 0

Process called "extract_response_size" that takes span as TraceContext returns Integer:
    Note: Extract response size from span tags
    If "http.response.size" in span.tags:
            Return string_to_integer with string as span.tags["http.response.size"]
    Otherwise:
            Return 0

Process called "extract_retry_count" that takes span as TraceContext returns Integer:
    Note: Extract retry count from span tags
    If "retry.count" in span.tags:
            Return string_to_integer with string as span.tags["retry.count"]
    Otherwise:
            Return 0

Process called "extract_circuit_breaker_state" that takes span as TraceContext returns CircuitBreakerState:
    Note: Extract circuit breaker state from span
    If "circuit_breaker.state" in span.tags:
            Let state_string be span.tags["circuit_breaker.state"]
    If state_string = "open":
            Return Open
    Otherwise if state_string = "half_open":
            Return HalfOpen
    Otherwise:
            Return Closed
    Otherwise:
            Return NotApplicable

Note: Error Analysis Helper Functions
Process called "find_primary_error_span" that takes error_spans as List[TraceContext] returns TraceContext:
    Note: Find the primary error span (root cause)
    If length of error_spans = 0:
    Return create_empty_span Note: Find error span with earliest timestamp (likely root cause)
            Let primary_span be error_spans[0]
    For each span in error_spans:
    If span.start_timestamp < primary_span.start_timestamp:
            Set primary_span to span Return primary_span

Process called "extract_exception_from_span" that takes span as TraceContext returns TracebackCore.ExceptionInfo:
    Note: Extract exception information from span
    Note: This would typically reconstruct from span tags and logs
    Return TracebackCore.ExceptionInfo with:
            exception_type as span.tags.get with key as "error.type" and default as "UnknownError"
            exception_message as span.tags.get with key as "error.message" and default as "Unknown error occurred"
    stack_frames as list containing Note: Would extract from logs
            cause_chain as list containing
            timestamp_nanoseconds as span.start_timestamp
            thread_id as 1
            process_id as 1
            severity_level as TracebackCore.Error
            category as TracebackCore.RuntimeError
            suggestions as list containing
            metadata as dictionary containing "span_id" as span.span_id, "service" as span.service_name

Process called "identify_affected_services" that takes trace as DistributedTrace and error_span as TraceContext returns List[String]:
    Note: Identify services affected by error
    Let affected_services be list containing error_span.service_name Note: Find services that called the error service and failed
    For each call in trace.call_chain:
    If call.callee_service = error_span.service_name and call.status_code > or equal to 400:
    If call.caller_service not in affected_services:
    Add to affected_services call.caller_service Note: Find downstream services that were impacted
    For each span in trace.all_spans:
    If span.status = Error and span.service_name not in affected_services:
    Note: Check if this error occurred after the primary error
    If span.start_timestamp > error_span.start_timestamp:
            Add to affected_services span.service_name Return affected_services

Process called "determine_root_cause_service" that takes propagation_chain as List[ErrorPropagation] returns String:
    Note: Determine which service is the root cause
    If length of propagation_chain = 0:
    Return "unknown" Note: Root cause is the service at the start of propagation chain
            Let first_propagation be propagation_chain[0]
            Return first_propagation.source_service

Process called "determine_propagation_mechanism" that takes source as TraceContext and target as TraceContext returns PropagationMechanism:
    Note: Determine how error propagated between services
    Let protocol be determine_call_protocol with caller as source and callee as target If protocol = HTTP or protocol = GRPC:
            Return DirectCall
    Otherwise if protocol = MessageQueue:
            Return AsyncMessage
    Otherwise if "timeout" in target.tags:
            Return Timeout
    Otherwise:
            Return DirectCall

Process called "analyze_error_transformation" that takes source as TraceContext and target as TraceContext returns ErrorTransformation:
    Note: Analyze how error was transformed between services
            Let source_error_type be source.tags.get with key as "error.type" and default as "Unknown"
            Let target_error_type be target.tags.get with key as "error.type" and default as "Unknown"
    Let severity_change be if source_error_type = target_error_type then Unchanged else Escalated Return ErrorTransformation with:
            original_error_type as source_error_type
            transformed_error_type as target_error_type
            context_added as dictionary containing "service" as target.service_name
            information_lost as list containing
            severity_change as severity_change
            metadata as dictionary containing "source_service" as source.service_name, "target_service" as target.service_name

Note: Impact Assessment Functions
Process called "filter_primary_affected_services" that takes affected_services as List[String] and trace as DistributedTrace returns List[String]:
    Note: Filter services that are primary affected (directly failing)
    Let primary_services be list containing For each service_name in affected_services:
    For each span in trace.error_spans:
    If span.service_name = service_name:
    If service_name not in primary_services:
            Add to primary_services service_name Return primary_services

Process called "filter_secondary_affected_services" that takes affected_services as List[String] and primary_services as List[String] returns List[String]:
    Note: Filter services that are secondarily affected
    Let secondary_services be list containing For each service in affected_services:
    If service not in primary_services:
            Add to secondary_services service Return secondary_services

Process called "assess_user_facing_impact" that takes trace as DistributedTrace and affected_services as List[String] returns UserFacingImpact:
    Note: Assess impact on user-facing functionality
    Let user_facing_services be identify_user_facing_services with services as affected_services If length of user_facing_services = 0:
    Return NoUserImpact Note: Check error rate in user-facing services
    Let error_rate be calculate_error_rate_for_services with trace as trace and services as user_facing_services If error_rate > or equal to 0.5:
            Return CompleteFailure
    Otherwise if error_rate > or equal to 0.2:
            Return PartialFailure
    Otherwise if trace.performance_metrics.p95_latency_ns > 5000000000: Note: >5s
            Return SlowResponse
    Otherwise:
            Return NoUserImpact

Process called "identify_affected_business_transactions" that takes trace as DistributedTrace returns List[String]:
    Note: Identify affected business transactions
    Let business_transactions be list containing Note: Identify business transactions from span operation names
    For each span in trace.all_spans:
    If span.operation_name contains "checkout" or span.operation_name contains "payment":
            Add to business_transactions "E-commerce Transaction"
    Otherwise if span.operation_name contains "login" or span.operation_name contains "auth":
            Add to business_transactions "User Authentication"
    Otherwise if span.operation_name contains "search" or span.operation_name contains "query":
            Add to business_transactions "Search Operation"
            Return remove_duplicates with list as business_transactions

Process called "estimate_revenue_impact" that takes business_transactions as List[String] and user_impact as UserFacingImpact returns Float:
    Note: Estimate revenue impact in dollars
            Let base_impact be if user_impact = CompleteFailure then 10000.0
            otherwise if user_impact = PartialFailure then 5000.0
            otherwise if user_impact = SlowResponse then 1000.0
    otherwise 0.0 Note: Multiply by number of affected business transactions
            Let transaction_multiplier be length of business_transactions
    If transaction_multiplier = 0:
            Set transaction_multiplier to 1 Return base_impact times transaction_multiplier

Process called "assess_recovery_complexity" that takes trace as DistributedTrace and affected_services as List[String] returns RecoveryComplexity:
    Note: Assess complexity of recovery
            Let service_count be length of affected_services
    Let error_span_count be length of trace.error_spans If service_count > or equal to 5 or error_span_count > or equal to 10:
            Return RequiresArchitecturalChange
    Otherwise if service_count > or equal to 3 or error_span_count > or equal to 5:
            Return ComplexManual
    Otherwise if service_count > or equal to 2:
            Return SimpleManual
    Otherwise:
            Return Automatic

Process called "generate_mitigation_strategies" that takes trace as DistributedTrace and affected_services as List[String] returns List[String]:
    Note: Generate mitigation strategies for distributed error
    Let strategies be list containing Note: General strategies
            Add to strategies "Implement circuit breakers for failing services"
            Add to strategies "Add retry logic with exponential backoff"
    Add to strategies "Enable request hedging for critical paths" Note: Service-specific strategies
    If length of affected_services > 3:
            Add to strategies "Consider graceful degradation for non-critical services"
    Add to strategies "Implement bulkhead pattern to isolate failures" Note: Performance-specific strategies
    If trace.performance_metrics.p95_latency_ns > 5000000000:
            Add to strategies "Optimize slow operations identified in critical path"
            Add to strategies "Implement request timeout and deadline propagation"
            Return strategies

